descript.abstract: This dataset depicts the point locations of street and park trees, along with stumps and vacant planting sites. Davey Resource Group performed a public tree inventory for the City of Ann Arbor from February-April, 2009. Data concerning these trees have been collected and analyzed, providing information about species composition, condition, and maintenance requirements.

attr.attrdef: FACILITYID was the number used to uniquely identify each tree, stump, or vacant planting space.
CommonGenus refers to the common genus name of the tree.
CommonName refers to the full common name of the tree.
BotanicalGenus refers to the botanical (scientific) genus identification of the tree.
Botanical refers to the botanical (scientific) genus and species identification of the tree.
Cultivar means 'cultivated variety' indicating whether the tree was specifically cultivated for a desirable attribute.
OnStreet refers to the actual street on which the tree is located.
FromStreet refers to the closest cross street prior to the tree's location when following the flow of street traffic.
ToStreet refers to the closest cross street after the tree's location when following the flow of street traffic.
Site refers to the number of the tree at a particular address, in relation to the other trees at that address alone.

Assigned refers to whether an address needed to be assigned to a tree's location or an actual physical address was able to be obtained. 'YES' means the surveyor approximated an address. 'NO' means a real street address was used.
AddressNumber refers to the number on the street address of the parcel where the tree is located.
Street refers to the name of the street where the parcel that contains the tree is located.

Location refers to the tree's general physical location, and may be 'Street', 'Borderline', or 'Park or Public Space'. A location of 'Borderline' means that the surveyor could not concretely determine whether the tree was located in the public right-of-way, or the tree belonged to the adjacent private property. In such cases, future investigation by staff will be needed to determine whether the tree is public or privately owned.
X_COORD means 'X coordinates' and refers to the east/west coordinate location of the tree in feet, using Projected Coordinate System NAD_1983_StatePlane_Michigan_South_FIPS_2113_IntlFeet
Y_COORD means 'Y coordinates' and refers to the north/south coordinate location of the tree in feet, using Projected Coordinate System NAD_1983_StatePlane_Michigan_South_FIPS_2113_IntlFeet.
WarrantyDate refers to the date that the warranty is up for a newly planted tree.
Ownership refers to the owner of the tree.

edom.edomvd: These trees have defects that cannot be cost effectively or practically treated, have a high amount of deadwood, and pose an immediate

These trees are not as great of a liability as Priority 1 Removals, being smaller and/or less hazardous, although they are also recommended for removal. Davey recommends that they be removed as soon as possible.

Trees designated for Priority 3 Removal do not pose a public hazard and are small, dead, or poorly formed. Smaller dead trees and failed transplants are in this category. Large trees in this category are generally poorly sited, of inferior quality, and pose little to no threat to the community.
Trees in this category need pruning to remove hazardous deadwood limbs greater than four inches in diameter and/or have broken, hanging, or diseased limbs.
These trees need pruning to remove hazardous deadwood limbs greater than two, but less than four, inches in diameter.
Trees in this category have characteristics that could become risks if not corrected. Deadwood limbs are less than two inches in diameter.
This category includes small growing trees that can generally be maintained from the ground, i.e., crabapples, serviceberry, dogwood, etc., and other trees 20 feet or less in height.

This category includes trees under 20 feet tall with correctable structural problems or minor amounts of deadwood that pose minimal threat of personal injury or property damage. Inexpensive pruning at this stage significantly affects the future of these trees. Young trees in this category that will be large at maturity generally require an annual pruning or inspection.

Data on vacant planting sites is collected using policies on minimum tree lawn width for mature tree size, spacing between trees, distances from intersection and traffic safety signs, and the presence of utilities.
Stumps are identified separately since they may not be removed at the time of a tree removal.

attr.attrdef: Maintenance refers to the maintenance need of each individual tree, classified into one of the following recommended maintenance categories.

edom.edomvd: most trees in this category require an annual inspection for several years. A healthy tree obviously impacted by recent construction serves as a prime example. This tree will need annual evaluations to assess the impact of construction on its root system. Another example would be a tree with a defect requiring additional equipment for investigation.

attr.attrdef: Inspect indicates whether or not the tree should have annual inspection.

edom.edomvd: 100% to 90% condition class. The tree is nearly perfect in condition, vigor, and form. This rarely used category is generally applicable to small DBH trees or shrubs that have been recently transplanted and are well established. It also applies to large trees that have established themselves successfully in the landscape.

89% to 80% condition class. Overall, the tree is healthy and satisfactory in condition, vigor, and form. The tree has no major structural problems, no mechanical damage, and may only have insignificant aesthetic, insect, disease, or structure problems.
79% to 61% condition class. The tree has no major structural problems, no significant mechanical damage, may have only minor aesthetic, insect, disease, or structure problems, yet is in good health.

40% to 21% condition class. The tree appears unhealthy and may have structural defects such as codominant stems, severe included bark, or severe trunk and/or limb decay. A tree in this category may also have severe mechanical damage, crown dieback, or poor vigor threatening its ability to thrive. Trees in poor condition may respond to appropriate maintenance procedures, although these procedures may be cost?prohibitive to undertake.

20% to 1% condition class. The tree has a major structural problem that presents an unacceptable risk, has very little vigor, and/or has an insect or disease problem that is fatal and, if not corrected, may threaten other trees on the property.
0% condition class. This category refers to dead trees only.

attr.attrdef: Condition indicates the current state of a tree's health, structural soundness, overall shape, and growth rate. Symptoms of poor condition include discoloration, decay, dieback, decreased internodal length, and/or disfigured or necrotic stems or roots. To some extent, condition class is also a reflection of the life expectancy of the tree. Crown development, trunk condition, major branch structure, twig growth rate, insects/diseases, and root condition are all considered. In general, the condition of each tree is recorded as one of the following categories adapted from the rating system established by the International Society of Arboriculture® (ISA).
ConditionDate was the date when the ConditionTreeHealth was assessed.
DBH2009 means the 'diameter at breast height' in 2009. Diameter is measured to the nearest inch in one-inch size classes at 4½ feet
DBH refers to the dbh of the tree in a range of 5-inch size classes.
DBHDate was the date when the dbh was measured.
Height refers to the height of the tree within one of the following ranges: 0-10'; 10-20'; 20-30'; 30-50'; 50-70'; >70'.
HeightDate was the date when the tree's height was measured.
TreePlantDate refers to the date when the tree was planted.
TreeValue refers to the appraisal value of the tree if it were damaged and in need of replacement.
TreeProgram refers to the name of the program that sponsored the planting of the tree.
ManagementArea is the geographic region of the City where the tree is located.
InstalledBy indicates who planted the tree, whether it is a City employee or a volunteer.
PestType indicates, for a diseased tree, the disease type.
OverheadUtilities indicates the presence of utilities at the tree site that may be in danger of being damaged.

PotentialSawLog indicates the potential for utilizing a portion of the tree for purposes other than chipping, i.e. for lumber production. Trees with saw log potential have at least 8' of wood usable for these purposes.
Comments are any general comments referring to the tree.
DataOrigin refers to the original source of the tree's data.
CreatedUser refers to the person who first created the attribute.
DateCreated was the date that the tree attribute was first created.
DateModified was the date that the attribute was last modified.
ModifiedUser was the person who last modified the attribute.

procstep.procdesc: Davey Resource Group performed a public tree inventory for the City of Ann Arbor from February-April 2009, using a combination of handheld computer-based mapping (GIS), GPS locators connected to the handheld computer, and field judgment to best determine information about species, condition, maintenance requirements, and location.
